<p>The <b>Republic of Indian Stream</b> was an <a href="/wiki/List_of_historical_unrecognized_states#Americas" title="List of historical unrecognized states">unrecognized</a> constitutional republic in <a href="/wiki/North_America" title="North America">North America</a>, along the section of the US–Canada border that divides the Canadian province of <a href="/wiki/Quebec" title="Quebec">Quebec</a> from the US state of <a href="/wiki/New_Hampshire" title="New Hampshire">New Hampshire</a>. It existed from July 9, 1832 to 1835. Described as <i>"Indian Stream Territory, so-called"</i> by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Census,_1830" title="United States Census, 1830" class="mw-redirect">United States census</a>-taker in 1830, the area was named for <a href="/wiki/Indian_Stream" title="Indian Stream">Indian Stream</a>, a small watercourse. It had an organized elected government and constitution, and served about three hundred citizens.</p>
<p></p>
